#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:1
msgid "Macro changes"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.31](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.31-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:5
msgid "`macro_rules!` style macros"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:7
msgid ""
"In Rust 2018, you can import specific macros from external crates via `use` "
"statements, rather than the old `#[macro_use]` attribute."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:10
msgid ""
"For example, consider a `bar` crate that implements a `baz!` macro. In `src/"
"lib.rs`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:20
msgid "In your crate, you would have written"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:23
#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:60
msgid "// Rust 2015\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:33
msgid "Now, you write:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:36
#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:71
msgid "// Rust 2018\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:45
msgid ""
"This moves `macro_rules` macros to be a bit closer to other kinds of items."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:47
msgid ""
"Note that you'll still need `#[macro_use]` to use macros you've defined in "
"your own crate; this feature only works for importing macros from external "
"crates."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:51
msgid "Procedural macros"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:53
msgid ""
"When using procedural macros to derive traits, you will have to name the "
"macro that provides the custom derive. This generally matches the name of "
"the trait, but check with the documentation of the crate providing the "
"derives to be sure."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:57
msgid "For example, with Serde you would have written"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:68
msgid "Now, you write instead:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:79
msgid "More details"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:81
msgid ""
"This only works for macros defined in external crates. For macros defined "
"locally, `#[macro_use] mod foo;` is still required, as it was in Rust 2015."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:84
msgid "Local helper macros"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:86
msgid ""
"Sometimes it is helpful or necessary to have helper macros inside your "
"module. This can make supporting both versions of rust more complicated."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:89
msgid ""
"For example, let's make a simplified (and slightly contrived) version of the "
"`log` crate in 2015 edition style:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:94
#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:217
msgid "/// How important/severe the log message is.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:105
#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:228
msgid "\"warning\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:106
#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:229
msgid "\"error\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:110
#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:233
msgid "// A helper macro to log the message.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:116
#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:239
msgid "\"{}: {}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:119
#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:242
msgid "/// Warn level log message\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:127
#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:250
msgid "/// Error level log message\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:137
msgid ""
"Our `__impl_log!` macro is private to our module, but needs to be exported "
"as it is called by other macros, and in 2015 edition all used macros must be "
"exported."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:140
msgid "Now, in 2018 this example will not compile:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:146
msgid "\"error message\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:150
msgid ""
"will give an error message about not finding the `__impl_log!` macro. This "
"is because unlike in the 2015 edition, macros are namespaced and we must "
"import them. We could do"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:157
msgid ""
"which would make our code compile, but `__impl_log` is meant to be an "
"implementation detail!"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:159
msgid "Macros with `$crate::` prefix."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:161
msgid ""
"The cleanest way to handle this situation is to use the `$crate::` prefix "
"for macros, the same as you would for any other path. Versions of the "
"compiler >= 1.30 will handle this in both editions:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:170
msgid "// ...\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:174
msgid ""
"However, this will not work for older versions of the compiler that don't "
"understand the `$crate::` prefix for macros."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:177
msgid "Macros using `local_inner_macros`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:179
msgid ""
"We also have the `local_inner_macros` modifier that we can add to our "
"`#[macro_export]` attribute. This has the advantage of working with older "
"rustc versions (older versions just ignore the extra modifier). The downside "
"is that it's a bit messier:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:192
msgid ""
"So the code knows to look for any macros used locally. But wait - this won't "
"compile, because we use the `format_args!` macro that isn't in our local "
"crate (hence the convoluted example). The solution is to add a level of "
"indirection: we create a macro that wraps `format_args`, but is local to our "
"crate. That way everything works in both editions (sadly we have to pollute "
"the global namespace a bit, but that's ok)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:199
msgid ""
"// I've used the pattern `_<my crate  name>__<macro name>` to name this "
"macro, hopefully avoiding\n"
"// name clashes.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:210
msgid ""
"Here we're using the most general macro pattern possible, a list of token "
"trees. We just pass whatever tokens we get to the inner macro, and rely on "
"it to report errors."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:213
msgid "So the full 2015/2018 working example would be:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/macros/macro-changes.md:268
msgid ""
"Once everyone is using a rustc version >= 1.30, we can all just use the "
"`$crate::` method (2015 crates are guaranteed to carry on compiling fine "
"with later versions of the compiler). We need to wait for package managers "
"and larger organisations to update their compilers before this happens, so "
"in the mean time we can use the `local_inner_macros` method to support "
"everybody. :)"
msgstr ""
